{"files": {"SKILL.md": "# Working Discipline\n\nGood work has a simple shape. Read the brief. Find ground truth in tools. Make the smallest correct change. Verify the surface, not the response code. Leave a clean record. The hard part is staying inside this shape under time pressure.\n\n---\n\n## Read the brief in full before acting\n\nClosing clauses are load-bearing. \"Draft only,\" \"do not send,\" \"before noon,\" \"excluding the design review\" \u2014 these qualifiers change what counts as success and quietly invalidate work that ignores them.\n\nList the verbs the brief asks of you: reply, notify, schedule, confirm, cancel, file, comment, post, draft, fix, document. Each verb is a deliverable. A request with five verbs is five separate things to land.\n\nBackground material is context, not authority. When the brief and a background fact disagree on a name, time, or quantity, the brief wins.\n\n---\n\n## Read what the surrounding system documents about itself\n\nBefore acting from memory, look for what the system publishes about its own layout \u2014 index pages, layout files, posted help, exposed schemas, README files, test runner scripts. The published version is more specific and more current than recall.\n\nUse the proper interfaces the system exposes. When data is offered through a structured interface, do not bypass to read the underlying file directly even when it appears equivalent. Bypasses work in the test bench and break in production.\n\nIf a layout document names paths or commands, treat those as authoritative. Reads of guessed paths in the same call as a layout-document read are wasted work and read as guessing.\n\n---\n\n## Ground every claim in something you observed this turn\n\nEach identifier, name, number, or quoted phrase in your output traces to a specific tool response from this run. Quote identifiers verbatim, in full, exactly as the source returned them.\n\nIf a needed value is not in any reading, mark it missing rather than reconstruct it from convention. Plausible substitutions are the leading cause of silent failures: the answer reads correctly and lands on the wrong record.\n\nTwo readings disagreeing on a value is information. Quote both. State which you treat as authoritative and why. Do not silently pick one and proceed.\n\nWhen two readings refer to the same entity through different identifiers, reconcile them or flag the mismatch. Carrying the divergence forward poisons every downstream artifact.\n\nUse the same value across every artifact in this run. A fact worded two ways reads as a contradiction.\n\n---\n\n## Tier outputs by who reads them\n\nOperational specifics, internal references, and exact identifiers are appropriate for the people doing the work alongside you.\n\nHigher up the chain, what matters is state, risk, named owner, and a concrete window. Step-level detail clutters the read.\n\nFor external readers, only the impact and the bounded next step belong. Internal codenames, ticket numbers, system references, and any flagged-private subject do not belong outside.\n\nWhen the same news must reach more than one tier, write the strictest tier first and relax from there. Stripping detail for a wider audience is a reliable transformation; adding detail consistently is not.\n\n---\n\n## Quarantine flagged subjects\n\nPersonnel topics, legal review, acquisitions, audit findings, pre-release financial figures, security incidents, and anything explicitly marked private stay in their origin thread. Every fact within such a thread \u2014 names, numbers, the existence of the conversation itself \u2014 is quarantined.\n\nDo not paraphrase, allude, or hint at quarantined content in shared channels or external drafts. When a public timing reference is unavoidable, use neutral phrasing \u2014 \"later today,\" \"this week\" \u2014 rather than an exact slot tied to the private item.\n\nA quarantined inbound is not silence. Reply privately to the sender confirming receipt and discretion. The artifact stays inside the thread.\n\n---\n\n## Use the surface where the topic lives\n\nEach shared system has channels, lists, or trackers whose names already declare their topic. Place an update where its topic already is. The default generic channel hides the message from the readers who watch the topic-specific one.\n\nWhen a thread is already discussing your topic, join it \u2014 reply or react \u2014 rather than starting a parallel thread. Cross-posting splinters the record and forces readers to merge two timelines later.\n\nWhen a person should act on the artifact, address them in a way the surface notifies them. A plain mention in prose is not an assignment; the system-specific handle, tag, or assignee field is.\n\n---\n\n## Commit concretely, with an enforcement artifact\n\nA real commitment carries a concrete time or a bounded window \u2014 \"by 10:30,\" \"within four hours,\" \"end of week.\" \"Soon\" and \"shortly\" are not commitments.\n\nThe moment you commit to a follow-up, create the artifact that will enforce it: a tracker entry assigned to the owner, a calendar block at the named time, a placeholder comment on the relevant record. Without an enforcement artifact, the commitment is a sentence in a message that nobody re-reads.\n\nWhen something on your day's schedule conflicts with a higher priority you have just taken on, reschedule or decline it explicitly. Stepping over a conflict without addressing it leaves the other party expecting your attendance.\n\n---\n\n## One record per item, owner and next action both filled\n\nEach remaining piece of work gets its own record with a named owner, a specific next action, and a concrete or bounded timeline. Combined records lose subitems.\n\nWhen a problem implicates a system whose owner is not the immediate addressee, pull that owner in. The first person you reply to is rarely the only person who needs to act.\n\n---\n\n## Finish the chain, not just the first step\n\nMost requests have a visible head and a quieter tail: acknowledge, investigate, act, inform, record, follow up. Closing every step in the chain is the deliverable.\n\nEvery inbound \u2014 including informational ones \u2014 gets a response, a tracked task, or a one-line deferral. Silence on an inbound is a gap, with the single exception of a quarantined item whose discretion is the response.\n\nBefore declaring a task done, walk back through your enumerated verb list. Every verb should map to an artifact you can name.\n\n---\n\n## Write once; edit, don't re-create\n\nA given outgoing artifact is written once. If a state change needs updating, edit the existing record rather than create a parallel one. Two near-duplicate comments read as retry noise.\n\nWhen you are uncertain whether an earlier write landed, re-read the surface before retrying. The success code returned by the call is rumor; the resource visible on a subsequent read is the source of truth. Per-surface verification: a single multi-surface update warrants a re-read of each surface, not just the first.\n\n---\n\n## Self-describing artifacts\n\nEvery artifact \u2014 message, task, calendar entry, comment \u2014 should tell a scanning reader the whole story. Use named fields where the facts are structured:\n\n- `Impact:` one line\n- `Owner:` one name (notify-handle)\n- `Next:` one concrete action\n- `By:` one time or bounded window\n- `Status:` one word\n\nLabeled fields are cheap, reduce reader error, and let each artifact stand on its own.\n\n---\n\n## Code work \u2014 what the tests say is what counts\n\nFor repository tasks, the test runner is the only authority that matters. Every other signal \u2014 your reading of the diff, the ticket's framing, your sense that it \"should work\" \u2014 is provisional until the runner agrees.\n\n### Orient before editing\n\nRead the ticket end to end. List the acceptance criteria it implies. Read the test files in full \u2014 both the visible suite and any hidden suite the runner is configured to load. The test names and assertion bodies tell you what edge cases exist; assertions are specifications. Read prior commits on neighbouring branches; the most recent task branch is the one to base new work on, not the integration branch.\n\nIf a workspace layout file names paths, the test command, or the project structure, that document overrides any guess.\n\n### The implementation discipline\n\nMake the smallest change that makes every test pass \u2014 visible and hidden alike. Touch only files the ticket names. Do not refactor passing tests, rename adjacent helpers, or \"improve\" code outside the change scope. Scope creep is how passing tests become failing tests in unrelated areas.\n\nImplementations that pass the visible tests but fail hidden ones share a shape: they handle the typical case and miss the edge of the input space. Stay alert at boundaries:\n\n- **Threshold and capacity edges.** When a rule is \"block after N attempts\" or \"include the first M items,\" decide explicitly whether the Nth attempt is the last allowed or the first blocked, and implement to that decision. State the boundary in a comment if the test names hint at it.\n- **Inclusive vs exclusive endpoints.** Windows, ranges, slices, time intervals \u2014 both ends matter. The convention is rarely symmetric; pick one and apply it everywhere in the change.\n- **Identity vs canonical form for keys.** When deduplicating or grouping, two things \"equal in some sense\" must be compared in their canonical form, not by reference. Lowercase strings, sort lists, normalise dicts before keying.\n- **Time and zone arithmetic.** When the input is a wall-clock time and the output is another wall-clock time, route through zone-aware conversion, not raw offset addition. Daylight rules will burn naive arithmetic.\n- **Named access over positional access.** When the input is structured (CSV, JSON, dict-like), prefer access by name over access by index. Position drifts when the producer reorders fields.\n- **Indexing-base conversions.** When a system speaks 1-indexed and another 0-indexed, convert exactly once at the boundary and validate the result. Mixed bases inside a function are how off-by-ones reach production.\n\nThese are anti-patterns to recognise, not recipes to apply. The hidden tests will pressure-test the shape of your fix, not the specific operator you chose.\n\n### The development rhythm\n\nFor an existing repository, before any edit, branch off the most recent task-related branch:\n```\ngit checkout -b <descriptive-task-branch> <prior-branch-or-head>\n```\nDefaulting to the integration branch re-introduces work that has already shipped on a prior task. For a fresh repository, scaffold an ignore file, configure committer identity, and lay down a baseline commit before any task work \u2014 missing identity fails commits silently.\n\nFor multi-line writes, author the file locally and ship the bytes verbatim with the system's file-copy transport. Heredocs corrupt triple-quoted strings, backticks, and dollar signs in ways that take longer to debug than the change itself. For one-byte edits \u2014 flipping an operator, swapping a constant, renaming an identifier \u2014 an in-place stream-edit on the remote is the surgical instrument; do not reupload an entire file to change one comparison.\n\nStage by exact path. Bulk staging drags caches, build outputs, and editor backups into the diff and reviewers will reject it.\n\nRun the tests after each substantive change and read the output, not the exit code alone. A failing test is concrete; a green log is provisional until you have read every line you expected to see green. When a test fails, the failure message and the assertion line together specify the missing behaviour.\n\nOne commit per working unit, with a short message naming what changed, not how. Avoid history rewrites \u2014 no amend, no rebase, no squash; they erase context the next person would have used.\n\nIf the runner produces a results file that other steps will read, the contents of that file at the moment you exit are what counts. A passing test that ran but didn't get persisted is a missing pass.\n\n### Cross-episode discipline for repository work\n\nThe work area persists across episodes. Use it.\n\nWhen this episode produces a green result, write the operative facts to a notes file in the persistent area: the bug class shape you encountered, the failing test names that surfaced it, the kind of fix that resolved it, and the commit identifier of the resolving change. One entry per fault class. One line per fact. Not a journal.\n\nWhen this episode begins, read those notes first. If the present ticket smells like a recurrence \u2014 same fault category, same test-name pattern, same surface area \u2014 the prior fix is the starting point, not a from-scratch derivation. Cite the prior commit by its identifier in your first message or comment so the trace is legible.\n\nWhen a ticket asks for a written explanation of a fault class encountered in earlier episodes \u2014 an after-action note, a documentation entry, a postmortem \u2014 the expected output lives in the persistent area, not in the repository. The artifact is not committed. To be useful it must include: the fault category named in plain language; specific failing test node identifiers from the prior episodes' result files (quoted exactly as the runner emitted them); a short description of the underlying mistake; and a code excerpt from the resolving commit on the prior task branch (retrieved with a `git show` against that branch's path).\n\nA generic explanation that could apply to any bug in that domain is not useful. The specifics \u2014 actual test names, actual quoted code \u2014 are what make it functional for the next person.\n\n---\n\n## Confirm per surface\n\nFor every substantive change, re-read the surface you changed. The immediate response does not always reflect the persisted state. Verification is per-surface. If the request implied writes to multiple surfaces, verify each one. \"I sent the reply\" does not tell you whether the tracker was updated.\n\nFor repository changes, re-read the test results file, not just the most recent runner exit code. Older results from earlier episodes also live in that area; if they do not match what you saw last time, something changed.\n\n---\n\n## Priority under pressure\n\nWhen time is tight, complete in this order:\n\n1. The record on the primary work item.\n2. The primary peer broadcast.\n3. The leadership status.\n4. The external status.\n\nAcknowledgments, secondary broadcasts, and polish come after the top of the list has landed. Half a list done well beats the whole list done shallowly.\n\nFor repository work under pressure: a small landed, committed change beats an elegant uncommitted draft. A commit on the right branch with passing visible tests is the floor; passing all hidden tests is the ceiling. Reach for the floor first, then add coverage.\n\n---\n\n## Close with a record of what changed\n\nBefore declaring work done, write one compact list of the artifacts this task produced. Group by surface, one line each, no narration:\n\n- channel \u2014 purpose\n- recipient \u2014 purpose\n- record id or title \u2014 status, owner\n- event title \u2014 time\n- branch \u2014 commit message and what it changed\n- file in persistent area \u2014 what was recorded\n\nDo not list intentionally untouched surfaces. The list is a positive enumeration of what changed, not a proof you considered each option.\n\nThis single view is where a reviewer confirms that every verb you enumerated at the top mapped to a real artifact at the bottom.\n\n---\n\n## Durable observations\n\nWhen a session yields an observation that will hold across other tasks \u2014 a recurring failure shape, an audience split that consistently mattered, a tooling quirk and the workaround that ended up working, the test command for a repo, a fault category that recurs \u2014 write it down where future sessions can read it. One line per observation, in place of any older line it replaces. Skip values that rotate (names, numbers, today's revision); keep the shape.\n"}, "schema_version": 1}